.Dd 2026-07-20
.Dt WT 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm wt
.Nd ncurses work-time stopwatch
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a small ncurses-based stopwatch for tracking work sessions.
Sessions are appended as rows to a CSV file under
.Pa ~/Documents/wt/
(the directory is created on first run).
.Pp
Each session is recorded as:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
date,start_time,end_time,description
.Ed
.Pp
Dates are
.Li YYYY-MM-DD ,
times are
.Li HH:MM
(minute precision).
The first line of the CSV is always a header; lines whose first field is not a
valid date are skipped on load, so manual edits, blank lines, and stray
comments are tolerated.
Descriptions containing commas, double quotes, or newlines are written with
RFC 4180 quoting, and have leading and trailing whitespace trimmed.
.Pp
The CSV is rewritten via
.Pa <file>.wt.tmp
(\(em
.Xr fflush 3 ,
.Xr fsync 2 ,
.Xr fclose 3 ,
.Xr rename 2
\(em
so a kill leaves the file with the last minute's data.
A running session's
.Li end_time
is rolled forward every wall-clock minute and flushed.
.Sh INTERACTION
.Nm
has three phases.
.Ss Picker
.Bl -tag -width "Enter" -compact
.It Sy Up Ns | Ns Sy k , Sy Down Ns | Ns Sy j
Move selection.
.It Sy Enter
Open the highlighted CSV.
.It Sy n
Create a new CSV (a
.Li .csv
suffix is appended if missing).
.It Sy q Ns | Ns Sy Esc
Quit
.Nm .
This is the only way to exit the program.
.El
.Ss Session list
.Bl -tag -width "Space" -compact
.It Sy Up Ns | Ns Sy k , Sy Down Ns | Ns Sy j
Move selection.
.It Sy Space
Start a new session.
Refused while the lock file exists (see
.Sx FILES ) .
.It Sy e
Edit the highlighted row's description.
.It Sy d
Delete the highlighted row after a
.Li y/N
confirmation.
.It Sy q Ns | Ns Sy Esc
Return to the picker.
.El
.Ss Running
A large
.Li HH:MM:SS
elapsed counter is shown and redrawn every second.
.Bl -tag -width "Space" -compact
.It Sy Space
Stop the session.
Refused while the description is empty (a beep is emitted and a hint is
shown).
.It Sy e
Edit the description of the running session.
.It Sy c
Cancel the session: drop the in-progress row and rewrite the CSV.
.It Sy q Ns | Ns Sy Esc
Refused with a hint to use
.Sy Space
(stop) or
.Sy c
(cancel).
.It Sy C-l
Redraw the screen.
.El
.Sh EDITOR
Description editing uses a custom readline-style line editor built on
.Xr ncurses 3 .
The current value is always prefilled.
.Bl -tag -width "M-b , M-f , C-<Left>" -compact
.It Sy Enter
Accept the input.
.It Sy Esc Ns | Ns Sy C-g
Cancel \(em the input is discarded.
.It Sy C-a , Sy Home
Move to the start of the line.
.It Sy C-e , Sy End
Move to the end of the line.
.It Sy C-b , Sy Left
Move one character left.
.It Sy C-f , Sy Right
Move one character right.
.It Sy M-b , Sy C-Left
Move one word backwards.
.It Sy M-f , Sy C-Right
Move one word forwards.
.It Sy C-d , Sy Delete
Delete the character under the cursor.
.It Sy C-h , Sy Backspace
Delete the character before the cursor.
.It Sy C-k
Delete from the cursor to the end of the line.
.It Sy C-u
Delete from the start of the line to the cursor.
.It Sy C-w
Delete the word before the cursor.
.It Sy C-t
Transpose the characters around the cursor.
.It Sy C-l
Redraw the screen.
.El
.Pp
.Dv ESCDELAY
is overridden to 250 ms internally so a lone
.Sy Esc
is recognized quickly.
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width "XDG_RUNTIME_DIR" -compact
.It Ev HOME
Used to locate
.Pa ~/Documents/wt/ .
.It Ev XDG_RUNTIME_DIR
Used for the lock file
.Pa wt.active ;
falls back to
.Pa /tmp
if unset.
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width "$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/wt.active" -compact
.It Pa ~/Documents/wt/
Directory holding CSV session logs.
One file per logical group, e.g.
.Pa work.csv ,
.Pa side-project.csv .
.It Pa $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/wt.active
.Pq or Pa /tmp/wt.active No if Ev XDG_RUNTIME_DIR No is unset
Lock file present while a session is running.
The first line is
.Li <PID> <stem>
followed by a newline, where
.Ar stem
is the basename of the selected CSV with
.Li .csv
stripped.
Its presence prevents
.Nm
from starting another session.
.It Pa <file>.wt.tmp
Temporary used for the atomic CSV replacement.
.El
.Pp
After writing the lock file,
.Nm
runs
.Xr pgrep 1
for
.Li bedstatus
and sends each match a
.Dv SIGUSR1
so the status bar re-reads the lock file immediately.
.Xr bedstatus 1
renders
.Li "[<stopwatch-icon> stem]"
between its BAT and TMR sections while the lock is held.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr bedstatus 1
.Sh BUGS
A
.Dv SIGKILL
(e.g.\&
.Xr kill 1
.Fl 9 )
of
.Nm
leaves the lock file behind; a manual
.Xr rm 1
is then required before a new session can start \(em no stale-lock recovery is
implemented.
.Pp
The lock file is written with plain
.Xr fopen 3 ,
not atomically, so a reader catching the write mid-flight may see a partial
line.
